    • keyword      : 0.375
    • bleu         : 0.028

  📝 Retrieved Answer:
  ----------------------------------------------------------
  SQL provides implicit row-level isolation guarantees by default. This means that when you execute a SELECT statement, the database ensures that you see only the data that was committed before your transaction started. This is known as the "read committed" isolation level.
  
  The other isolation levels (read uncommitted, read committed with serializable, and repeatable read) are provided explicitly by the user or the application, and they offer more detailed control over the transaction's visibility of data. However, they are not the default behavior for SELECT statements in SQL.
  
  It's important to note that the default isolation level can be changed using the SET TRANSACTION ISOLATION LEVEL statement, allowing you to choose the level that best suits your application's requirements.
  ----------------------------------------------------------

